Gemini suggestion
1. The "Subprocess Pipe" Strategy (Most Robust)
This is the gold standard for open-source video projects.
You use OpenCV for the processing (the math/color logic) but pipe the raw frames into a standalone FFmpeg process for encoding.

Why it works: Users only need to install a standard ffmpeg binary (available on every OS via brew, apt, or choco),
which natively handles high-res HEVC.

Code Pattern:

Python
import cv2
import subprocess as sp

# Setup the FFmpeg command
cmd = [
    'ffmpeg', '-y',
    '-f', 'rawvideo', '-vcodec', 'rawvideo',
    '-s', f'{width}x{height}', '-pix_fmt', 'bgr24', '-r', '30',
    '-i', '-',  # Input comes from stdin
    '-c:v', 'libx265', '-crf', '18', '-pix_fmt', 'yuv420p',
    'output.mp4'
]

process = sp.Popen(cmd, stdin=sp.PIPE)

